    1/**
    2 * Immutable arbitrary-precision integers. All operations behave as if
    3 * BigIntegers were represented in two's-complement notation (like Java's
    4 * primitive integer types). BigInteger provides analogues to all of Java's
    5 * primitive integer operators, and all relevant methods from java.lang.Math.
    6 * Additionally, BigInteger provides operations for modular arithmetic, GCD
    7 * calculation, primality testing, prime generation, bit manipulation,
    8 * and a few other miscellaneous operations.
    9 *
    10 * <p>Semantics of arithmetic operations exactly mimic those of Java's integer
    11 * arithmetic operators, as defined in <i>The Java Language Specification</i>.
    12 * For example, division by zero throws an {@code ArithmeticException}, and
    13 * division of a negative by a positive yields a negative (or zero) remainder.
    14 * All of the details in the Spec concerning overflow are ignored, as
    15 * BigIntegers are made as large as necessary to accommodate the results of an
    16 * operation.
    17 *
    18 * <p>Semantics of shift operations extend those of Java's shift operators
    19 * to allow for negative shift distances. A right-shift with a negative
    20 * shift distance results in a left shift, and vice-versa. The unsigned
    21 * right shift operator ({@code >>>}) is omitted, as this operation makes
    22 * little sense in combination with the "infinite word size" abstraction
    23 * provided by this class.
    24 *
    25 * <p>Semantics of bitwise logical operations exactly mimic those of Java's
    26 * bitwise integer operators. The binary operators ({@code and},
    27 * {@code or}, {@code xor}) implicitly perform sign extension on the shorter
    28 * of the two operands prior to performing the operation.
    29 *
    30 * <p>Comparison operations perform signed integer comparisons, analogous to
    31 * those performed by Java's relational and equality operators.
    32 *
    33 * <p>Modular arithmetic operations are provided to compute residues, perform
    34 * exponentiation, and compute multiplicative inverses. These methods always
    35 * return a non-negative result, between {@code 0} and {@code (modulus - 1)},
    36 * inclusive.
    37 *
    38 * <p>Bit operations operate on a single bit of the two's-complement
    39 * representation of their operand. If necessary, the operand is sign-
    40 * extended so that it contains the designated bit. None of the single-bit
    41 * operations can produce a BigInteger with a different sign from the
    42 * BigInteger being operated on, as they affect only a single bit, and the
    43 * "infinite word size" abstraction provided by this class ensures that there
    44 * are infinitely many "virtual sign bits" preceding each BigInteger.
    45 *
    46 * <p>For the sake of brevity and clarity, pseudo-code is used throughout the
    47 * descriptions of BigInteger methods. The pseudo-code expression
    48 * {@code (i + j)} is shorthand for "a BigInteger whose value is
    49 * that of the BigInteger {@code i} plus that of the BigInteger {@code j}."
    50 * The pseudo-code expression {@code (i == j)} is shorthand for
    51 * "{@code true} if and only if the BigInteger {@code i} represents the same
    52 * value as the BigInteger {@code j}." Other pseudo-code expressions are
    53 * interpreted similarly.

    55 * <p>All methods and constructors in this class throw

    892/**
    893* Squares the contents of the int array x. The result is placed into the
    894* int array z. The contents of x are not changed.
    895*/
    8961var squareToLen = BigInteger.squareToLen = function (x, len, z) {
    897 /*
    898 * The algorithm used here is adapted from Colin Plumb's C library.
    899 * Technique: Consider the partial products in the multiplication
    900 * of "abcde" by itself:
    901 *
    902 * a b c d e
    903 * * a b c d e
    904 * ==================
    905 * ae be ce de ee
    906 * ad bd cd dd de
    907 * ac bc cc cd ce
    908 * ab bb bc bd be
    909 * aa ab ac ad ae
    910 *
    911 * Note that everything above the main diagonal:
    912 * ae be ce de = (abcd) * e
    913 * ad bd cd = (abc) * d
    914 * ac bc = (ab) * c
    915 * ab = (a) * b
    916 *
    917 * is a copy of everything below the main diagonal:
    918 * de
    919 * cd ce
    920 * bc bd be
    921 * ab ac ad ae
    922 *
    923 * Thus, the sum is 2 * (off the diagonal) + diagonal.
    924 *
    925 * This is accumulated beginning with the diagonal (which
    926 * consist of the squares of the digits of the input), which is then
    927 * divided by two, the off-diagonal added, and multiplied by two
    928 * again. The low bit is simply a copy of the low bit of the
    929 * input, so it doesn't need special care.
    930 */
    93141 var zlen = len << 1;
    93241 if (z == null || z.length < zlen)
    93314 z = Common.intArray(zlen);
    934
    935 // Store the squares, right shifted one bit (i.e., divided by 2)
    93641 var lastProductLowWord = 0;
    93741 for (var j=0, i=0; j<len; j++) {
    938621 var piece = Long.fromNumber(x[j] >>> 32);
    939621 var product = piece.multiply(piece);
    940621 z[i++] = (lastProductLowWord << 31) | product.shiftRightUnsigned(33).low;
    941621 z[i++] = product.shiftRightUnsigned(1).low;
    942621 lastProductLowWord = product.low;
    943 }
    944
    945 // Add in off-diagonal sums
    94641 for (var i = len, offset = 1; i > 0; i--, offset += 2) {
    947621 var t = x[i-1];
    948621 t = mulAdd(z, x, offset, i-1, t);
    949621 addOne(z, offset-1, i, t);
    950 }
    951
    952 // Shift back up and set low bit

    95641 return z;
    957}

    1515/**
    1516 * Returns a BigInteger whose value is x to the power of y mod z.
    1517 * Assumes: z is odd && x < z.
    1518 */

    1520/*
    1521 * The algorithm is adapted from Colin Plumb's C library.
    1522 *
    1523 * The window algorithm:
    1524 * The idea is to keep a running product of b1 = n^(high-order bits of exp)
    1525 * and then keep appending exponent bits to it. The following patterns
    1526 * apply to a 3-bit window (k = 3):
    1527 * To append 0: square
    1528 * To append 1: square, multiply by n^1
    1529 * To append 10: square, multiply by n^1, square
    1530 * To append 11: square, square, multiply by n^3
    1531 * To append 100: square, multiply by n^1, square, square
    1532 * To append 101: square, square, square, multiply by n^5
    1533 * To append 110: square, square, multiply by n^3, square
    1534 * To append 111: square, square, square, multiply by n^7
    1535 *
    1536 * Since each pattern involves only one multiply, the longer the pattern
    1537 * the better, except that a 0 (no multiplies) can be appended directly.
    1538 * We precompute a table of odd powers of n, up to 2^k, and can then
    1539 * multiply k bits of exponent at a time. Actually, assuming random
    1540 * exponents, there is on average one zero bit between needs to
    1541 * multiply (1/2 of the time there's none, 1/4 of the time there's 1,
    1542 * 1/8 of the time, there's 2, 1/32 of the time, there's 3, etc.), so
    1543 * you have to do one multiply per k+1 bits of exponent.
    1544 *
    1545 * The loop walks down the exponent, squaring the result buffer as
    1546 * it goes. There is a wbits+1 bit lookahead buffer, buf, that is
    1547 * filled with the upcoming exponent bits. (What is read after the
    1548 * end of the exponent is unimportant, but it is filled with zero here.)
    1549 * When the most-significant bit of this buffer becomes set, i.e.
    1550 * (buf & tblmask) != 0, we have to decide what pattern to multiply
    1551 * by, and when to do it. We decide, remember to do it in future
    1552 * after a suitable number of squarings have passed (e.g. a pattern
    1553 * of "100" in the buffer requires that we multiply by n^1 immediately;
    1554 * a pattern of "110" calls for multiplying by n^3 after one more
    1555 * squaring), clear the buffer, and continue.
    1556 *
    1557 * When we start, there is one more optimization: the result buffer
    1558 * is implcitly one, so squaring it or multiplying by it can be
    1559 * optimized away. Further, if we start with a pattern like "100"
    1560 * in the lookahead window, rather than placing n into the buffer
    1561 * and then starting to square it, we have already computed n^2
    1562 * to compute the odd-powers table, so we can place that into
    1563 * the buffer and save a squaring.
    1564 *
    1565 * This means that if you have a k-bit window, to compute n^z,
    1566 * where z is the high k bits of the exponent, 1/2 of the time
    1567 * it requires no squarings. 1/4 of the time, it requires 1
    1568 * squaring, ... 1/2^(k-1) of the time, it reqires k-2 squarings.
    1569 * And the remaining 1/2^(k-1) of the time, the top k bits are a
    1570 * 1 followed by k-1 0 bits, so it again only requires k-2
    1571 * squarings, not k-1. The average of these is 1. Add that
    1572 * to the one squaring we have to do to compute the table,
    1573 * and you'll see that a k-bit window saves k-2 squarings
    1574 * as well as reducing the multiplies. (It actually doesn't
